Step 2.

OK, but you should explain people have to ream them, an 8mm drill but better a reamer !
I designed bushings too to replace the chinese LM but I used Igus filament and it works great. Yes about any plastic will somewhat "work" but why not make something better ???? I don't like PLA, soften with T°, better stay below 55°. It seizes easily, just drilling or screwing in it causes seizing.
I didn't copy the LM form factor because I wanted to make them smaller and integrated in the parts. I am amazed at the bulk of the carriage people "design"
Babbitt is one of the first to come with the notion of "soft" bearings and defined somewhat the requirements. Do a search.
The LM bearings issue is mainly due to the soft SS rods which are out of specs ! Used with the right rods, they are OK but of course nothing like the Misumi. Of course always noisier than bushings.

description.text:
This is a keychain toy, it's a remix of another one I saw but I can't find it anymore.
It's simple and fun to do.

Good luck
-Wallie
NGSS CCSS

What is it and what will you learn? It's an easy and fun toy for on your keychain.
You'll learn the basics of SolidWorks and how to make holes, threads, combine, ETC. Once you know what you're doing to remake it from scratch it took about 1 hour.
To do for the first time about 2-2.5 It's a fun and easy project as a lesson or as homework.

Steps i took to make this. I started with the base I made a hexagon of 2.5cm wide and 0,5 long Then I added a circle of 2cm wide and 5cm long. I made a hole in the top of the circle 1,5 wide and 1,8 long. Thread the hole however you want (it's not too hard just trail and error). Thread the outside of the circle however you want (I used Metric Die M10x1.0 0,10cm between) Done with Base Save as Part (*.prt) And as STL If you want to print later. The top screw Again start with a hexagon 2,5 wide 0,5 tall Extruded base make a circle in the middle 1,5 wide 1,7 long (This way you can be sure it screws in all the way) Now Click Insert (Left top of the screen then a little to the right)
-Part
-Add Base
MAKE SURE Locate part with Move/Copy feature is on.
Align the hexagons perfectly Move item over the Y Axes till the top hole of the base Just Barely doesn't touch the hexagon. Now go to -Insert -Features -Combine
-Subtract
-Main body = Screw
-Body to combine = Base -Okey Now safe as part and as STL -Nut Hexagon 2.5 by 0,5
Make hole in middle 1,9cm wide (Hole wizard)
Insert - Part: Base - Align hexagon to hexagon - Use Y Axes to move - Make sure nut is centered.
Combine - subtract - Main = Nut - Body to combine = Base
Okey Now safe as part and STL Now you can make assembly File - make assembly Insert base Insert Nut Mate - Concentric - Click between threads on the nut - Click on the thread on the base. Okey Mate - Concentric - Select same - Go to Mechanical mates - Screw - Distance/revolution Insert whatever you selected as the space between threads (or whatever you feel like) Now spin the nut till it's on the base. -Insert components
Insert the top screw Mate - Concentric - Click between threads on Screw - Click on the thread on the base. Okey Mate - Concentric - Select same - Go to Mechanical mates - Screw - Distance/revolution Insert whatever you selected as the space between threads (or whatever you feel like) Now spin the nut till it's on the base. I wish you the best of luck!
-Wallie

You need SolidWorks to follow the steps I took at least.

description.text:
I dislike having the filament spool - which is heavy - above the printer as a source of vibration. In looking for another place to put the spool I decided to fit it onto one of the side braces I use. This puts the spool onto a rigid structure and since it's much lower down it's also much less likely to induce vibration into the system.

There are three main parts:

  1. Spool holder - self-taps for M8 and M1o rods with a single nut to lock it in position.
  2. Bowden tube guide 1 - self-taps for M10 with a bolt to lock. Takes a 2/4mm Bowden tube
  3. Bowden tube guide 2 - self-taps for M10 with a large hole to provide a loose guide.

I've used about 75cm of PTFE tubing and the Parametric spool holders with M8 bearings.

title: Animated Snowman

description.text: Animated Snowman, abominable style. Stands a "huge" 22cm (approximately 8.25") tall. Video of prototype is here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U05AEIvywCA. Video of final version here:http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ihdkCsRMJHQ Video of underlying mechanism is here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rnBX_tLLp3I. I designed this for the elementary school I attended 50 years ago to illustrate what can be accomplished with mathematics, imagination, creativity, and a 3D printer. Designed using Sketchup 8 (free version) and printed in PLA using Makerware and a Replicator 2.

Purchased items: 1) "6VDC 45 RPM Pinky Finger Sized Gear Motor 1" Long x 15/32" x 3/8"" from either amazon.com or directly from http://sciplus.com/p/MICROMOTOR_47952. Other sources are available, I've not tested them though. 2) Coaxial Power Jack - Radio Shack part number 274-1583. 3) 3 Vdc Power Supply - Radio Shack part number 273-315. 4) 22 gauge wire. 5) Stick on rubber feet. Assembly notes: Study "Assembly.skp", a Sketchup 8 (free version) file. The body parts and hat were designed at a thickness of .8mm in order to minimize both weight and print time. I've included both "Body.stl", and the separated body pieces "Body Upper.stl" and "Body Lower.stl". If "Body.stl" does not print on your printer (e.g. it is too tall), print the separate pieces "Body Upper.stl" and "Body Lower.stl" and glue them together using cyanoacrylate glue. Roughen the contacting surfaces of the two "Eccentric Large.stl" parts and "Lifter.stl" part with 120 grit sandpaper. After roughening, if your Snowman does not swing the full 90 degrees, glue a disc of 120 grit sandpaper to the bottom surface of "Lifter.stl" (I ended up doing this). Glue "Hat.stl" onto "Head.stl" in whatever position you desire. Once the mechanism is assembled and tested (see video), slide the body (either "Body.stl" or "Body Upper.stl" and "Body Lower.stl" glued together), onto the mechanism, and insert the arms through the openings in the upper body into "Arm Pivot.stl". The body hangs freely on the arms which is intentional in order to minimize amplification of the noise generated by the gear motor, and to allow a rocking motion during animation. Operate the mechanism and when working, tack glue the head assembly to the top using cyanoacrylate. Only a couple of drops should be used in order to allow removal of the head with a modeling knife in case maintenance and/or adjustment is required. I used a permanent ink marker to color the eyes, nose, mouth and buttons onto the final assembly. Everyone has more artistic capabilities than I, so I'm expecting to see a serious improvement in this area! Finally, to keep the Snowman from walking off the desk, I applied stick on rubber feet to the underside of "Base.stl". Don't hesitate to comment if you have any questions. Enjoy.

description.text:
This is a first version of a drainage plug for a couple of planters in our garden, to hopefully aid water in draining out of the soil. Our planters have a roughly 1-inch diameter hole in the bottom, this is intended to be inserted from beneath as the soil and plants are already in place - but getting very waterlogged.

This model contains my logo as an artistic element. It is NOT OK to sell prints of this Thing, except in the Shapeways / 3dHubs type of "rent a printer" way, where the provider of 3d printing service is not providing the 3d model. If you want to create your own model from scratch based on the ideas visible from the STL file, that is of course absolutely fine (although I would appreciate a Remix tag, if you put your model on Thingiverse).

I have not yet printed this (awaiting delivery of my first printer) so I can't be sure if it will function as intended or even print correctly. Once oriented in CraftWare it seems to slice OK - there are some areas where small bridges will be required, and I would suggest adding some manual supports to help the centre top part. No other supporting should be needed, unless your printer demands use of a raft. There's a little chamfer on the edge to help in removing it from the print bed. I am hoping that it can be printed with zero infill, if 2 or 3 top+bottom layers are used - the structure of the holes should help brace the inner and outer shells well enough.

The Fusion 360 project can be imported from the .F3Z file. To do this in Fusion, open the Data Panel, go in to a Project, click the little cloud Upload button, select the .f3z - it will upload in to your Fusion 360 account and then you can open it.

Be aware I'm very new to Fusion 360 and I am certain there are better ways to do a lot of the things in the file. See the "How I Designed This" section for a bit of a walk-through.

Introduction

I used Autodesk Fusion 360 for this project. It's a beast of an application, but for hobbyists and start-up companies it's free - and by the time I got to the end of making this Thing I was totally sold on the power-vs-difficulty tradeoff.

I have uploaded a screenshot of each step in the Fusion Timeline. This isn't going to show you how to use the Fusion 360 tools, but just walk through the steps of which ones I used in what order and why.

Note I'm going to be using "the 3d printing names" for axes rather than what Fusion 3D may be calling them. X/Y are the build platform and Z is up.

Profile sketch of revolved solids Sketch solids to revolve

From an empty file, I created a sketch on the XZ plane and drew out my initial solids of revolution in cross-section.

The main object solid is the right-hand part - the section on the left was created as a "helper" and isn't included in the STL. I'm pretty certain it ended up not being necessary for the construction, but I used it and so I can't throw it away.

There are a lot of Dimensions on this sketch to make it easier to adjust sizes later without having to do a lot of manual changing. Dimensions are awesome and if you're going to use Fusion 360 then you should use them. I ended up needing to change some dimensions after the construction was basically complete, so just being able to edit Dimensions in this sketch and have most things auto-adjust to match was super nice.

Revolve the relevant sketch faces around the Z axis (not shown, also revolve the Helper Cylinder in a SEPARATE operation) Construct a Tangent Plane, tangent to the Helper Cylinder (main body is hidden), using the XZ plane as the Helper Plane to set angle Construct an Offset Plane, set back a couple of mm from that Tangent Plane On that offset plane, behind the Tangent Plane (now hidden), Sketch the cross-sectional shape of the intended holes. (See Conclusion section for more) Construct a Plane At Angle, using the bottom straight line of that sketch as the Line and set the angle to 45 degrees. Then sketch a straight line on that new plane, starting at the corner where this plane crosses the other one and there's a line from the other sketch Sweep the enclosed face on the earlier sketch on the Offset Plane along the single line on that 45 degree plane. This makes a Create a Circular Pattern of that new Hole Positive body, centred around the Z axis. This makes copies spread nicely out. Construct a Plane At Angle, going through the Z Axis and set to an angle of 22.5 degrees Select the 4 Explanation: Why mirror them in a plane?

As you will see in the next steps (and in the finished Thing) I wanted an offset "second row" of holes in my pattern.

It turns out, it's really difficult to get Fusion 360 to let you manually move things around, if they were created by a Pattern command operation. Initially I had tried copying just 1 of the Hole-bits up (with Rectangular Pattern), but I couldn't then Move it to rotate it around the Z axis.

Eventually I hit on a bit of geometry cheating. By reflecting the 4 parts in a plane set at half of the angular offset I wanted, this puts the mirror clones at "fake 45 degrees" to the originals. As the things I'm mirroring in the plane are all identical and symmetrical, it works as a fake-rotate for my needs here.

(I'm sure there's a better way to do this. Damned if I know what it is, though!)

Move the Mirror-created parts up a bit, to create an offset pattern. As I'm moving them all together, the software let me do this. Use Rectangular Pattern to copy all 8 of those Hole Positive bodies up the desired distance and number of repetitions. As I realised I wanted more holes further down the item, but it would have been quite a nuisance to edit the original sketch and hope things behaved, I just used another Rectangular Pattern command Un-hide the main Body part and use Combine to Cut where all of those Hole Positives stick through. The Helper Cylinder was not included in the operation (main part was already hollow) and is now hidden I could have stopped there, but I chose to add a big Hole to cut through the tip of the cone on top. The Hole was actually placed on the X/Y plane, at the Origin, and set to cut All On the XZ plane, sketch out the profile for the inside-top bits. I don't really know if this stuff will serve any functional benefit, or be a problem. I just felt like doing this stuff. Extrude that sketched profile and use the Symmetric option so it expands evenly from the centre. Use Circular Pattern to create a rotated copy of the extruded piece Stick a little chamfer on the outer edge of the base, just in case that helps getting it off the print bed later (maybe a bigger one would be needed?) Conclusion

That's it - the walk through of the timeline steps in this Thing!

There was a LOT of going back and adjusting "earlier things" to make later steps fit properly. Not many measurement decisions were correct the first time round. But as Fusion 360's Timeline makes it easy to re-do things like that and have consequent changes propagate forward, it was not too annoying to do.

For instance, it wasn't until I got a the first STL into a slicer and checked it there, that I realised a tiny part of the outsides of the cut holes would be unprintable. Due to the geometry involved, projecting a purely rectangular Hole through the side of a cylinder at an angle produced a slight "sharp tip" on the tops of the holes. This would have resulted in a non-printable (or stupidly support-requiring) overhang.

So, I went back to the Hole Profile Sketch (image 4 above) and changed the top Line to a 3-point Arc, then tweaked the Arc Radius until I got a flat-enough top edge to the projected holes. And as the initial Sweep to extend that surface out in to a "hole positive" immediately updated with the change, and then the Circular Pattern, Mirror, Rectangular Pattern and Combine results all propagated the change along, the result was I could change the shape of all the cut-out holes just by making changes to one Sketch.

Now I look back at it, the inner "helper cylinder" was not required at all. I could have simply put the Tangent Plane directly on the main outer cylinder face and set the Offset Plane behind it back a bit further and got the same results with a bit less complexity. I can't delete it now though, as all the Hole-Positive geometry relies on it.

Fusion 360 is a complicated beast and I'm sure I've only scratched the surface here, but I am now thoroughly convinced it's worth the effort to learn.

title: BALLOON BOAT
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text: This water-running boat is a simple way of learning about the use of compressed air as a source of propulsion. It illustrates the concept of thrust and introduces a practical method to achieve a sealing solution with the intention to throttle air flow.

THRUST In a similar way that air is used to push this boat through water, airplanes get propelled through air. This type of propulsive force is known as THRUST. Its computation is very important in the aeronautics world and we think you would like to know how it is achieved.
Let’s take a look first at what is happening. The balloons apply a force to the air in the form of pressure and force it to exit. Even though the air does exit, it resists movement and applies a force back to the balloons equal in magnitude but in the opposite direction. An action is followed by a reaction. This is Newton’s third law! Since the balloons are attached to the strider, the air’s reaction is effectively transferred on to it and this is what causes it to move in the opposite direction. Action and reaction are equal in magnitude so computing the force exerted on the air (action) will tell us how much thrust is applied to the boat (reaction). To quantify the force exerted on the air you need to understand Newton’s second law and, for this you need to first be introduced to the concept of “momentum”. A body of mass (m) moving at a certain velocity (v) has a momentum equal to the product of these two (mv). So we can increase the momentum of an object by either increasing its speed or increasing its mass. Think of a snowball rolling down the mountain. As it rolls it grows larger in mass and so its momentum increases (it is also speeding up…).
In its purest form, Newton’s second law states that a force is needed to make an object change its momentum over time. The value of such force is equal to the change of momentum desired over the time desired. So if we want a resting tennis ball to change its velocity to 5 m/s and achieve this in a process lasting 1 second, we will have to exert 10 times more force than if we wanted it to acquire the same velocity after 10 seconds. When the object moving is a solid, it is very easy to think of the change in momentum as the product of the mass and the acceleration (hence the F=ma). But when it’s a fluid like air, we take the “snowball” approach. Sitting outside the strider, we see air mass exiting the strider at a certain velocity being increasingly delivered to the atmosphere. So the change in momentum of the air can be related to the change in mass moving at a given velocity. This change of mass over a given period of time is what is known as mass flow. There is a flow of mass of air exiting the balloons of the strider, there is a flow of mass of air reincorporating to the atmosphere… If we think that the velocity of the air exiting the strider does not change with time during deflation (not an accurate approximation for our balloons but certainly for an aircraft engine!) we can re-write Newton’s second law for thrust computation (See Figure 1): All we need now is to know the exit velocity of the air and compute the flow of air mass. We can know how much air volume flows out of the boat's valve if we know the area of the exhaust port and the air velocity. The product of the volume flow and the density equals the mass flow. So given that we know rho = 1.275 kg/m3 and the exit port of the stride is 32mm2, really the key thing to know is the exit velocity of the air. Using two balloons of 200mm of diameter we have measured the exit velocity through the valve exhaust port fully opened. It takes about 10s to deflate. See the curve we have obtained in the Figure below: In rough terms we can then estimate that the force on the strider using two balloons is 0.002N or 19.2 gf (grams-force, nearly the same as the weight of AA battery). Perhaps not a lot, but definitely enough to move the strider. If no other forces would be acting on the strider, by the end of the 10 s period that it takes for the balloons to deflate, the velocity of the strider would be 312 mm/s: Unfortunately, Thrust is not the only force acting on the strider movement. There is Gravity, Buoyancy and Drag. Drag is a force due to the friction between the strider body and the water. It depends on the area of the cross section of the floaters that is immersed in water. Although we won’t try to compute Drag here, we can say that your strider will travel faster is less cross sectional area is exposed to the water. More reason then, to try to balance it properly. What else could be subject to drag? Are the balloons offering a large cross section area against wind? How would air drag compare to water drag on the body?

LEARN BY STEPS The recommended order to impart this lesson is: 1) THEORY: go over the concepts and the general ideas
2) 3D PRINTING
3) POST-PROCESSING: work on the valve to remove the central wall. Make sure the screw attaches properly to the valve. Else remove any exceeding material.
4) ASSEMBLE: make a seal by cutting off a balloon nozzle (see pics). Follow the drawing (.pdf) to assemble and use screws M3x8. Balance boat to minimize Drag (see pics below)
5) TEST: ready to run!

title: Gear O'Clock - number plates and couple of changes

description.text: Following on from Bad Brad's Gear O'Clock (amazing) and VeryWetPaint's accessories (brilliant), I have produced two plates - one for the odd numbers and one for the even numbers - dimensions still in inches. There are another couple of files here too which I hope will help people with home build reprap machines - I am using a RepRapPro Huxley. In order to slice the open top mechanism housing and the main drive gear from VeryWetPaint using Slic3r and Skeinforge I found that I had to rotate them through 180 degrees in the Z direction before I could get a print - the files here are the ones from VeryWetPain but rotated as above. Bearing in mind that I am working in mm and that that PrintTo3D and VeryWetPaint are working in inches, I used the scale option in Slic3r for my two clocks. The first clock, which I wanted to mount on my desk divider at work was scaled at x20 and I used a scale of x25 for my other one - this is the maximum size for my RepRapPro Huxley - the ClockBaseDiv4 STL from VeryWetPaint is excellent and just about fits on my print bed at x25. I amended VeryWetPaint's slotted drive gear as I purchased a clock movement with circular push fit type shafts. (Here in the UK, the only movement I could find with a slotted minute shaft was VERY expensive and so I used movements from www.ClockParts.co.uk - a lot cheaper!). The file here, (which has a drive gear scaled at x20 from the original) has a 3.6mm hole which pushes on to the minute shaft: no need to remove the hour shaft. This part has a 26mm diameter face and takes the second hand gear scaled at full size. At first, I started printing numbers using a single colour, intending to paint them but after reading Stephen Cropp's very well documented technique for splitting GCode in order to print multicolours, decided to become a purist and make my clock 100% plastic, no paint! http://stephen.cropp.co.uk/category/3d-printing/

For those working in mm, print the main clock mechanism at a scale of 25.4 no matter what scale you use for the rest of the parts otherwise it will not fit the clock mechanism.  
Scale the numbers plates to whatever scale factor you use for the main dial and main drive gear.  
The only "already scaled" STL file is that for the main drive gear with the 3.6mm push fit hole. This is for a x20 scale clock which gives a numbers gear at approximately 8in diameter.  
ClockMechanismMountOpenTop is identical to VeryWetPaint's file apart from being rotated 180degrees in the Z axis - which I needed to do in order to slice in Slic3r and Skeinforge.

comments.author: jeankil

comments.text: Dear Jean... we're afraid this could be hard to achieve. It really comes down to the type of motors you could get. As a rule of thumb, the total thrust (x4 propellers) on a quadcopter should be twice it's weight. At ~8,000 RPM, each prop achieves 30gf which would be only good to lift a 60 grams vehicle (30 x 4 / 2)....really low capability considering battery and motor weight, let alone structure. Thrust does scale with the square of speed so lighter motors spinning faster would be the first thing to look into, but there's a chance that around 16,000 RPM the hub might begin to crack (excessive centrifugal pull from the blades). You have however, given us an idea for the future and we'll be tinkering with a lighter, more "lifty" prop design.We'll keep you posted.

http://s1191.photobucket.com/user/Billfedderson/media/VIDEO0042_zps0d54f9ec.mp4.html
Some parts had to be epoxied together (the uprights that hold the false floor up and the wheel since I printed it in two halves). The tub, pump, light and marbles were all purchased at a local hardware store. (McGuckins), though I have modeled the tub if you guys have access to a way to print something that large. The two 'plates' that make the bridge are printed in such a way that they support each other. I wish I could have found a vitamin-less spindle setup.. but this spindle is a r/c helicopter-blade balancer trapped in 2 608 bearings with custom mounts.
It is still a work in progress. Tell me what you guys think. :)

All models designed on Solidworks 2012, all 3D printed parts printed on a modified Makerfarm Prusa I3 8" kit. Wheel halves, and upright assemblies were epoxied together. A jig is included for the uprights. If you are trying to build one of your own, message me and I will do whatever I can to help. Thanks!

description.text: This is a fully parametric pet collar that has customized text printed on the outside. Being circular, much text can fit.

Measure your pet's neck with a string, add some slack, divide by pi , divide this by two,  and enter this as the radius. I am starting with r=37 for my cat. Add your pet's name, your address, and phone number to keep your pet safe! The latch mechanism is in test now (shove the wedge in place). Otherwise, you can use a plastic tie to secure the end.   
If you do not have scad, I recommend downloading it (openscad). Then open this scad file and press f6! It will render, then you can download the STL. Often the customizer on this website is down, getting this program is the sure way.

description.text:
these designs are to re-house the Arduino 2560&Ramps1.4 separate from the smart controller on the Poltur i3 Printer and give the printer a more compact and tidy finish.

the smart controller case also allows the builder to position the controller anywhere they choose on the frame or even externally if printer is enclosed.

obviously this designs can be used on any Ramps equipped printer, its by no means exclusive to the Poltur, its just what it was designed originally for.

I also incorperated a digital voltmeter display into the ramps case using this display:-

http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/Mini-0-36-3-Digital-LED-Display-Voltage-Meter-Voltmeter-DC-3-2-30V-Yellow-Volt-/261257340587?hash=item3cd426a6ab:g:uPoAAOxy-sRSWWxk

but should the builder not want to use one Ive also included a blanking part.

the display case front and back snap together tightly and dont allow the controller to move about inside once together but also have fixing holes if the builder wants a more permenant fix.

the ramps case lid has two slots for 40mm fans to snap into (one can be used if you prefer but I found too much cooling is better than too little)

both the rears of the ramps case and controller are open backed HEX patterned to allow for better cooling but also offer ample fixing points for mounting both, the nature of my Poltur printer allows me to simply zip-tie the pair where I choose too and they'll both be solid and secure.

title: Adjustable front facing Z limit switch mod for Tevo Tarantula

description.text:
This simple mod makes it easier to adjust the heights of the Z limit switch when the printer is accessible just fron the front side (e.g. when it is stored in an enclosure). there are two parts to be printed, one needs to be mounted directly on the X axis using the already available screws and the other is to be fixed on the external frame using additional screws and T-nuts. If the extruder is mounted on the same side of the frame (as in the picture), take care that the screw holder do not hit it while the X axis is raised.

NOTE:
I removed the metal part of the limit switch to have a cleaner switching point. However it was pointed out that an overshoot of the Z axis may damage the micro-switch and that anyhow the design works fine also with the metal part in place.

comments.text: I've made one.  The brackets work well for me.  However, I did not remove the metal arm on the micro-switch, as suggested by the original designer (RC-3D).  The flexible arm on the micro-switch is designed to protect the micro-switch from being damages if the Z Axis Carriage overshoots a little bit.  If the bolt acts directly on the micro-switch, the micro-switch could easily be wrecked if the Z Axis overshoots just a little bit.   With the metal arm on the micro-switch, this design works perfectly.
